<summary>
The <strong><c>&amp;lt;span&amp;gt;</c></strong> <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML">HTML</see> element is a generic inline container for phrasing content, which does not inherently represent anything. It can be used to group elements for styling purposes (using the <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Global_attributes#class"><c>class</c></see> or <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Global_attributes#id"><c>id</c></see> attributes), or because they share attribute values, such as <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Global_attributes#lang"><c>lang</c></see>. It should be used only when no other semantic element is appropriate. <c>&amp;lt;span&amp;gt;</c> is very much like a <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/div">div</see> element, but <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/div">div</see> is a <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Block-level_content">block-level element</see> whereas a <c>&amp;lt;span&amp;gt;</c> is an <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Inline-level_content">inline-level element</see>.
</summary>
